10.4: Hu Moments

Adrian

In computer vision and image processing, image moments are often used to characterize the shape of an object in an image. These moments capture basic information such as the area of the object, the centroid (i.e. the center (x, y)-coordinates of the object), the orientation, and other desirable properties.

In Ming-Kuei Hu’s 1962 paper, Visual Pattern Recognition by Moment Invariants, Hu proposed seven moments that can be used to characterize the shape of an object in an image. Hu further demonstrates that these moments are (theoretically) invariant to changes in rotation, translation (provided that a tight cropping of the object in the image is obtained), scale, and reflection (i.e. mirroring).

However, the term “invariance” needs to be taken very lightly. Moment based calculations are often sensitive to the initial calculation of the centroid (since all further moment calculations are centered around the initial centroid).

In real-world applications, this dependable and repeatable centroid is not easily obtained — and because of this centroid dependency, Hu Moments should not be used in situations where there is noise, occlusion, or a lack of (extremely) clean segmentation.

Standard image moments are implemented in OpenCV through the cv2.moments  function. Hu Moments are available via the cv2.HuMoments  function.

Objectives:

The primary objective of this lesson is to explore the Hu Moments image descriptor used to quantify the shape of an object in an image. We’ll then also create a computer vision project to detect outlier shapes in an image using Hu Moments.

What are Hu Moments used to describe?

Hu Moments are an image descriptor utilized to characterize the shape of an object in an image. The shape to be described can either be a segmented binary image or the boundary of the object (i.e. the “outline” or “contour” of the shape).

In general, the segmented binary shape is preferred to the boundary of the shape since it is less susceptible to noise (Dudani, et al.).

The Hu Moments descriptor returns a real-valued feature vector of seven values. These seven values capture and quantify the shape of the object in an image. We can then compare our shape feature vector to other feature vectors to determine how “similar” two shapes are.

How do Hu Moments work?

From a strictly statistical point of view, “moments” are just statistical expectations of a random variable. In fact, you’re probably already familiar with at least one moment, whether you realize it or not!

The most common moment is the first moment, the mean. You’re also very likely familiar with the second moment, the variance — and taking the square-root of the variance leaves us with the standard deviation, which you’re probably also familiar with. Skew and kurtosis round out the third and fourth moments, respectively.

We can then use this feature vector to compare against other feature vectors to determine if two shapes are “similar.”

Where are Hu Moments implemented?

Hu Moments are implemented inside the OpenCV library in the cv2.moments  and cv2.HuMoments  functions:

Computing Hu Moments

import cv2

How do I use Hu Moments?

Computing Hu Moments using the OpenCV library is relatively straightforward. As I mentioned above, we apply Hu Moments to either thresholded images or the silhouettes of objects generated via methods such as edge detection.

In this particular example, we’ll be computing Hu Moments for the silhouettes of the following 3 aircraft:

Figure 3: We’ll be computing Hu Moments for each of the 3 airplane shapes in this image.

We’ll be looking at a more in-depth and practical usage of Hu Moments later in this lesson, but for the time being, let’s familiarize ourselves with the cv2.moments  and cv2.HuMoments  functions before we tackle any larger project. Open up a new file, name it extract_hu_moments.py , and insert the following code:

extract_hu_moments.py

# import the necessary packages
import cv2
import imutils
 
# load the input image and convert it to grayscale
image = cv2.imread("planes.png")
image = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
 
# compute the Hu Moments feature vector for the entire image and show it
moments = cv2.HuMoments(cv2.moments(image)).flatten()
print("ORIGINAL MOMENTS: {}".format(moments))
cv2.imshow("Image", image)
cv2.waitKey(0)

Lines 6 and 7 simply load our planes.png  file from disk. The image has already been thresholded and the silhouettes are clearly visible, so we do not need to perform thresholding/edge detection. A simple conversion from the RGB color space to grayscale is all the pre-processing we need.

Lines 10-12 then demonstrate how to incorrectly compute Hu Moments for an image with multiple objects. Instead of taking into account the multiple aircraft in an image, Lines 10-12 compute Hu Moments for the entire image, which is (usually) not our intention. When we take the entire image into account like this, our shape statistics become completely irrelevant. Since Hu Moments are defined relative to their centroid, the centroid becomes the center of all three shapes rather than just one of them.

To correctly compute Hu Moments for each of the three aircraft silhouettes, we’ll need to find the contours of each airplane, extract the ROI surrounding the airplane, and then compute Hu Moments for each of the ROIs individually:

# find the contours of the three planes in the image
cnts = cv2.findContours(image.copy(), cv2.RETR_EXTERNAL,
cv2.CHAIN_APPROX_SIMPLE)
cnts = imutils.grab_contours(cnts)
 
# loop over each contour
for (i, c) in enumerate(cnts):
# extract the ROI from the image and compute the Hu Moments feature
# vector for the ROI
(x, y, w, h) = cv2.boundingRect(c)
roi = image[y:y + h, x:x + w]
moments = cv2.HuMoments(cv2.moments(roi)).flatten()
 
# show the moments and ROI
print("MOMENTS FOR PLANE #{}: {}".format(i + 1, moments))
cv2.imshow("ROI #{}".format(i + 1), roi)
cv2.waitKey(0)

To find each of the individual airplanes in the image, we first find the contours of the outlines on Lines 16-18.

We loop over each of the individual contours on Line 21 and then extract the ROI using the bounding box of the contour on Lines 24 and 25.

Given our ROI, we can now apply the cv2.moments  and cv2.HuMoments  functions on Line 26 to extract our shape features for each individual aircraft.

Finally, Lines 29-31 show the computed shape features associated with each aircraft.

To see our script in action, simply open up a terminal and execute the following command:

extract_hu_moments.py

First, you’ll see the output of (incorrectly) computing Hu Moments for an entire image:

Figure 4: Special care must be taken to compute Hu Moments for each shape individually. Here we are (incorrectly) computing Hu Moments for the entire image, which includes all three shapes.

Followed by computing Hu Moments for each of the three individual airplanes:

Figure 5: Notice how we have corrected our mistake in this example and have extracted a Hu Moments feature vector for each of the three shapes.

Not too complicated, right?

The most important aspect you need to keep in mind is the number of objects in an image.

If you are describing only one object in an image, you are safe to compute Hu Moments over the entire thresholded/edge map image.

However, if you are trying to quantify the shape of multiple objects in an image, you’ll need to extract the ROI for each object and compute Hu Moments over each individual ROI.

Finding outlier shapes with Hu Moments

Now that we have gotten our feet wet with Hu Moments, let’s use them to build an actual project.

In this particular project we are going to perform shape outlier detection. Given N images of shapes, our goal is to use Hu Moments to identify the one image in the dataset of N shapes that does not belong.

Obviously, our first step is to generate this dataset. We’re going to generate N (in this case, 500) random images of circles of various size and color. Then we’ll generate a single image of  rectangle:

Figure 6: Our dataset consists of many circles and only a single rectangle. Our goal is use Hu Moments to find the square needle in the haystack of circles.

As you can see in the above image we have many, many images of circles — but only one rectangle. Using Hu Moments we’ll be able to find this rectangle in our dataset.

Let’s go ahead and see how we are going to generate this dataset:

# import the necessary packages
import numpy as np
import argparse
import uuid
import cv2
 
# construct the argument parse and parse the arguments
ap = argparse.ArgumentParser()
ap.add_argument("-o", "--output", required=True,
help="Path to the output directory")
ap.add_argument("-n", "--num-images", type=int, default=500,
help="# of disctrator images to generate")
args = vars(ap.parse_args())
 
# loop over the number of distractor images to generate
for i in range(0, args["num_images"]):
# allocate memory for the image, then generate the (x, y)
# center of the circle, then generate the radius of the
# circle, ensuring that the circle is fully contained in
# the image
image = np.zeros((500, 500, 3), dtype="uint8")
(x, y) = np.random.uniform(low=105, high=395, size=(2,)).astype("int0")
r = np.random.uniform(low=25, high=100, size=(1,)).astype("int0")[0]
 
# randomly generate a color for the circle, draw it, and
# write the image to file using a random filename
color = np.random.uniform(low=0, high=255, size=(3,)).astype("int0")
color = tuple(map(int, color))
cv2.circle(image, (x, y), r, color, -1)
cv2.imwrite("{}/{}.jpg".format(args["output"], uuid.uuid4()), image)

Perhaps this code is better suited for the Drawing lesson of the PyImageSearch Gurus course, but I still think it’s important to review regardless. One of the best way to learn the OpenCV library is by looking at examples.

Lines 8-13 parse our command line arguments for us. We need two switches here: --output , which is the output directory to store our dataset of generated images; and a second switch, --num-images , which is an integer representing the number of random circle images we are going to generate.

Line 16 then starts looping over the number of random images we want to create for our dataset. At each iteration of the loop, we allocate memory for a NumPy array of size 500 x 500 on Line 21. We’ll then generate a random (x, y)-coordinate and a radius r for the circle we want to draw (while ensuring the entire circle will fit into the image) on Line 22 and 23.

We’ll also need a random color (i.e. a RGB tuple), so we’ll generate that on Lines 27 and 28 as well. Finally, Lines 29 and 30 draw the circle on our image and write the image to file with a completely random filename.

Let’s finish up this example by generating a single random rectangle:

This code is also straightforward — we simply generate a random (x, y)-coordinates for the top-left and bottom-right points for our rectangle, draw the rectangle using a random color, and then write the image to disk using a totally random filename.

And after the script has finished executing, you’ll have an output  directory filled with 501 images (500 images of circles; one of a rectangle):

Figure 7: After running our script, we now have a directory of images: 500 circles and 1 rectangle.

So tell me, would you want to go through all these images, one by one, to find the single image of a square?

I’m willing to bet that the answer is “Definitely not!”

In fact, there is no reason to. We can simply compute Hu Moments for each of these shapes, compare the features to each other, and then find the outlier.

Let’s go ahead and see how we can perform this outlier detection. Open up a new file, name it find_rectangle.py , and we’ll get started:

find_rectangle.py
Python
1

# import the necessary packages
from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import pairwise_distances
import numpy as np
import argparse
import glob
import cv2
import imutils

We start off by importing our necessary packages. Everything looks pretty standard — except for that pairwise_distances  function. What in the world does that do?

Well, as the name suggests, it computes the pairwise distances between a set of feature vectors and returns a distance matrix.

Given a set of N feature vectors, a pairwise distance function will compute the distances between each and every one of the N feature vectors — again, the output of this operation is called a distance matrix.

For example, let’s say we have a dataset of 3 feature vectors denoted as A, B, and C. To compute a distance matrix, we’ll take the distance, denoted as the function  between each one of the 3 feature vectors, as visualized below:

Figure 8: Computing an example distance matrix between the feature vectors A, B, and C. Notice how the distance matrix is symmetrical. The distance between A and B is the same as the distance between B and A.

Notice how the distance matrix is symmetrical — the distance is the same as . This is because a distance function/similarity metric should return the same result no matter the order of the supplied feature vectors. In practice, we can exploit this symmetry and only compute the upper/lower-triangular of the distance matrix.

However, instead of manually writing code to construct this distance matrix, we can simply use the pairwise_distances  function to compute it for us from the scikit-learn library. You can read more about the pairwise_distance  function here.

So why is computing distance matrix between Hu Moment feature vectors important?

Well, since Hu Moments are utilized to characterize the shape of an object in an image, we can assume that the distance between circles will be very small since they are visually similar to each other. On the other hand, we can assume the distance between the rectangle feature vector and all other circle feature vectors will be very large, since the rectangle is not as similar as all the other circles.

# construct the argument parse and parse the arguments
ap = argparse.ArgumentParser()
ap.add_argument("-d", "--dataset", required=True, help="Path to the dataset directory")
args = vars(ap.parse_args())
 
# grab the image paths from disk and initialize the data matrix
imagePaths = sorted(glob.glob(args["dataset"] + "/*.jpg"))
data = []
 
# loop over the images in the dataset directory
for imagePath in imagePaths:
# load the image, convert it to grayscale, and threshold it
image = cv2.imread(imagePath)
gray = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
thresh = cv2.threshold(gray, 5, 255, cv2.THRESH_BINARY)[1]
 
# find contours in the image, keeping only the largest one
cnts = cv2.findContours(thresh.copy(), cv2.RETR_EXTERNAL,
cv2.CHAIN_APPROX_SIMPLE)
cnts = imutils.grab_contours(cnts)
c = max(cnts, key=cv2.contourArea)
 
# extract the ROI from the image, resize it to a canonical size,
# compute the Hu Moments feature vector for the ROI, and update
# the data matrix
(x, y, w, h) = cv2.boundingRect(c)
roi = cv2.resize(thresh[y:y + h, x:x + w], (50, 50))
moments = cv2.HuMoments(cv2.moments(roi)).flatten()
data.append(moments)

We’ll parse our command line arguments on Lines 10-12. We’ll need a single switch, --dataset , which is the path to the directory of generated images from the generate_images.py  script above.

We’ll grab the paths to all these images on Line 15, followed by initializing a list named data . This list will hold the Hu Moments feature vectors for each of the shapes in the imagePaths  lists.

To quantify our dataset of shapes, we start looping over the image paths one by one on Line 19.

For each of them we’ll perform a bit of pre-processing — conversion to grayscale followed by thresholding will suffice:

Figure 9: We only need a bit of basic pre-processing here. Converting the image to grayscale and thresholding should suffice.

Given our thresholded image, we find the object in the image on Lines 26-29 using contours and extract the ROI. We’ll also resize our ROI to be a constant size of 50 x 50 pixels. It’s important to resize our ROI to a known size so that the features returned from Hu Moments are not influenced by the dimensions of our object. Simply put, we are obtaining scale invariance (i.e. the returned feature vector is not different for various sizes of an object) simply by resizing the ROI to a constant size. We don’t care about the size of the object itself, just the shape. This is a neat little trick that we often use in computer vision and image processing.

After resizing to a known, constant size, we can extract Hu Moments from the shape on Lines 34-36.

Finally, we update our data  matrix with the feature vector for the current shape on Line 37.

Now we can perform our actual outlier shape detection:

find_rectangle.py
Python

# compute the distance between all entries in the data matrix, then
# take the sum of the distances for each row, followed by grabbing
# the row with the largest distance
D = pairwise_distances(data).sum(axis=1)
i = np.argmax(D)
 
# display the outlier image
image = cv2.imread(imagePaths[i])
print("Found square: {}".format(imagePaths[i]))
cv2.imshow("Outlier", image)
cv2.waitKey(0)

The first step to detecting our outlier shape is to compute the distance matrix D using the pairwise_distances  function. For each and every Hu Moments feature vector in the data  list, we compute the Euclidean distance between the feature vectors.

This means that for the 501 images in our data  list, our distance matrix D has 501 x 501 entries which correspond to the distance between each of the feature vectors.

We’ll also go ahead and take the sum of each of the distances for each row in the distance matrix D.

Why would we do this?

Recall what I mentioned at the top of this section — when comparing circles to circles, the distance should be very small. But when comparing a rectangle to circles, the distance should be substantially larger.

So by taking the sum of all distances for a particular image, we can find the row of the matrix that has the largest summed distances (Line 43).

The row with the largest distance is thus our outlier, which we load and display to screen on Lines 46 and 48.

To see our outlier detection script run, just issue the following command:

find_rectangle.py
Shell
1
$ python find_rectangle.py --dataset output

Sure enough, you’ll see the following result:

Figure 10: Utilizing only Hu Moments we were able to disambiguate between the 500 circle shapes and find the single rectangle.

As you can see, we have been able to find the single rectangle image in an entire dataset of circles just by quantifying the shape of an object using Hu Moments.

Of course, we could also solve this problem using contour properties, but there are (almost) always multiple ways to solve a computer vision problem — using Hu Moments for shape outlier detection is just one of them.

Suggestions when using Hu Moments:

If you need to describe multiple shapes in an image, be sure to extract the ROI of each object, and then extract Hu Moments from each ROI as we did in the How do I use Hu Moments? section of this lesson.

Otherwise, simply load the image from disk, binarize it (using thresholding, edge detection, or conversion to grayscale), and then extract Hu Moments.

Take time to address whether or not extracting features from a single shape or multiple shapes in an image can have dramatic impact on how you write your code to extract Hu Moments feature vectors.

Hu Moments Pros and Cons

Pros:

  • Very fast to compute.
  • Low dimensional.
  • Good at describing simple shapes.
  • No parameters to tune.
  • Invariant to changes in rotation, reflection, and scale.
  • Translation invariance is obtained by using a tight cropping of the object to be described.

Cons:

  • Requires a very precise segmentation of the object to be described, which is often hard in the real world.
  • Normally only used for simple 2D shapes — as shapes become more complex, Hu Moments are not often used.
  • Hu Moment calculations are based on the initial centroid computation — if the initial centroid cannot be repeated for similar shapes, then Hu Moments will not obtain good matching accuracy.
